It may appear that there is a linear term in $H_\mathbf{u}$, viz., proportional to $g_{ab} \partial_a u_b = \Lambda_{ac}^{{\rm T}}\Lambda_{cb} \partial_a u_b$. However, using a property of Dirac delta functions, we can express the local incompressibility constraint in Eq.~(\ref{eq:Z}) as $\delta(\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}) = \det \underline{\underline{g}} \, \delta(\partial_a g_{ab} u_b)$. Let us define a new field $\mathbf{u}' \equiv \underline{\underline{g}}\cdot\mathbf{u}$, and the functional integral over $\mathbf{u}$ becomes a functional integral over $\mathbf{u}'$. In the new representation, the delta function constraint becomes $\delta(\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}')$ and the putative linear term in $H_\mathbf{u}$ becomes $\partial_a u_a^\prime$, and so the linear term vanishes. The vanishing of the linear term is thus connected to the local incompressibility of the elastomer. 

